Hello,

I have read the draft a few times, and have a few comments/questions:

1) is the ICMP message sent hop-by-hop towards the destinations, i.e. is the
IP addressed to each next-hop in turn for them to add data(link info)?

If the answer to this is 'No, it is sent to the final destinations', then I
have this question:

1a) If each router on the path to the destination is selecting packets at
random, the will select packets with different source addresses (if the DOS
attack is doing the usual thing if using invalid and varying addresses), so
would this actually be useful?

If the answer to 1) is 'Yes', then I have this question:

1b) This scheme would only be of any use if all routers implemented it...

A suggestion (probably considered already):
DOS attacks are best stopped at the 'customer edge', so could we just
recommend that edge devices implement some sort of reverse-path-routing
check, and take some configured action if the source address is 'wrong':

1) local/remote log and forward/drop packet
2) New 'Bad-Source' ICMP to monitor-node/final-destination and forward/drop
packet

Both of these actions could also be done infrequently as required, for
example sampling on 'reverse-path-failures to a given destination' and
limited that as a specific rate, as well as limiting the total number
generated for all destinations.

This would seem to get to straight to the problem and does not require all
router to comply. This could also be implemented in border gateways (BPG AS
boundaries) a given authority.

Sorry if this digs up old bodies...
Cheers, Steve. 

