> If the answer to this is 'No, it is sent to the final destinations', then I
> have this question:
> 
> 1a) If each router on the path to the destination is selecting packets at
> random, the will select packets with different source addresses (if the DOS
> attack is doing the usual thing if using invalid and varying addresses), so
> would this actually be useful?

The answer is NO for your question #1. While the source addresses can
be spoofed, the router ID (and other related information) for the
router producing this iTrace packet is harder to spoof (see the
authentication section).

The problem left is whether you can distinguish the "traced" packet is
normal or DDoS. This can be done, in a statistical or deterministic
fashion,
in different ways -- this is up to the "consumers" of iTrace
information. For
example, the source IP address does not exist. Or, if the attacker is
using a
fix 16 bit prefix source IP with randomized 16 bit suffix, then we can
identify the attack packets based on the signture. Exactly how this step
is
done is out of the scope of iTrace though.

> A suggestion (probably considered already):
> DOS attacks are best stopped at the 'customer edge', so could we just
> recommend that edge devices implement some sort of reverse-path-routing
> check, and take some configured action if the source address is 'wrong':
> 
> 1) local/remote log and forward/drop packet
> 2) New 'Bad-Source' ICMP to monitor-node/final-destination and forward/drop
> packet

There have been many schemes proposed to "detect/filter" "bad" source IP
addresses in the research community (e.g., UCLA and Purdue). I think
commercial routers allow us to do reverse-path lookup, at a cost of
performance though.

I personally believe that "ingress filtering" and "iTrace" can
complement
each other in the future.

-Felix

