Thanks for the reply.

If the DOS attack is using 'random' 'valid' source addresses, then this may
be difficult to put the itrace bits together. It seems to me that software
would need to track 'hanging TCP sessions' to a given protected server, and
see if any of the itrace message match src/dest-wise.

I think there is room to extend the functionality of any reverse-path-check
to invoke a 'could be bad' ICMP message (infrequently) and let the packet
through (in the same way that itrace suggests). As I say, I think this would
be a more selective/focused method of tracking DOS.

For DDOS, I guess the reverse-path-check could be useless since it may be
the case that there are innocent hosts involved and they are using their own
IP source. But for this case, determining the actual source is not an issue
anyway...

Cheers, Steve.
 

