On Thu, 16 Aug 2001, Waters, Stephen wrote:
> > I think RPF is all that useful against the whole Internet
> > only on systems
> > which have full routing table BUT only one connection to Internet.  I
> > think these are pretty rare by definition.
> >
> I'm not sure I understand your point here - could you tell it another way?

Sure..

A few scenarios (non-exhaustive, of course :):

1) site border router, with default route to internet, basic routes to
local LAN(s)
2) ISP core router, default route(s) to the internet, with bgp/igp routes
consisting of ISP networks providing redundancy and routing
3.a) ISP edge router, with default route outside, only one exit point
3.b) ISP edge router, with full internet routing table, only one exit
point
3.c) ISP edge router, with full internet routing table, two exit points to
upstream for redundancy

RPF check against Internet (and the local interfaces etc. can be handled
by access lists)  in 1), 2), and 3.a) are pretty much useless because
default route matches all.

3.b) RPF check would drop spoofed, non-advertised routes, but there is no
point in having full internet table if you could just do with default
route instead.  This is what I meant with rare by definition.

3.c) RPF check would be useful but it might work in unexpected ways under
failover (and/or asymmetric routing)

Hopefully this clarifies the point I was trying to make.

-- 
Pekka Savola                 "Tell me of difficulties surmounted,
Netcore Oy                   not those you stumble over and fall"
Systems. Networks. Security.  -- Robert Jordan: A Crown of Swords


