Lets please keep uRPF in context. It is one tool and a deterrent. When used
for BCP 38 filting, it works with asymmetrical routes, multihoming, and load
balanced packets. But, it is tool built into the forwarding logic of the
router (ASIC or software/CPU based). Punting or signaling packet drops from
uRPF upstream is a little more difficult to do - especially if you want at
"line speed" (which means ASIC forwarding at tomorrow's speeds).



