uRPF was designed for BCP 38 - for single homed and multihomed customers.
Most of the situations below are not BCP 38. The object was how to scale BCP
38. BCP 38 via ACLs is _not_ operationally scalable with today's deployment
tools and skill levels in the NOCs (you need people to maintain them). When
you talk to the ISPs and eliminate the "asymmetrical" and "multihoming"
excuses for uRPF on the edge, you get to the core problem - BCP 38 adds
complexity that factors into the resolution of any customer outage.

Bottom line - added complexity adds to the operational cost of a network.
Any ISP Security solution needs to be mindful that adding to the operational
complexity (hence cost) of a network is a barrier for implementation.


Barry


